Not by choice.

37:01.587 --> 37:02.686
Alzheimer's.

37:03.889 --> 37:05.522
What?

37:05.524 --> 37:07.524
I thought you had to be
really old to get that.

37:07.526 --> 37:09.826
Earlier onset is
what they call it.

37:09.828 --> 37:12.562
It's pretty common actually.

37:12.564 --> 37:14.297
How bad is she?

37:14.299 --> 37:16.516
Bad.

37:16.517 --> 37:18.734
Especially this last year,
I had to put her in a home.

37:18.737 --> 37:19.803
Shit.

37:21.306 --> 37:22.439
Your Mom was always
like Wonder Woman,

37:22.441 --> 37:23.673
doing a million things at once.

37:23.675 --> 37:24.941
There's no stoppin' her.

37:25.944 --> 37:26.843
That's so sad.

37:28.247 --> 37:29.646
You know, sometimes
I feel like I'm lucky

37:29.648 --> 37:31.648
to have this last
bit of time with her.

37:31.650 --> 37:33.883
Like it's a warning
or something.

37:33.885 --> 37:35.619
I'm getting the chance to
know that she won't be here

37:35.621 --> 37:37.154
much longer and I
can make the most

37:37.155 --> 37:38.688
of the time we
have left together.

37:39.758 --> 37:41.858
But it's such an awful disease.

37:41.860 --> 37:43.460
She's not even her anymore.

37:44.396 --> 37:47.497
I visit all the time and
when I leave I feel so sad.

37:47.499 --> 37:49.332
Unbalanced.

37:49.334 --> 37:51.768
It really weighs on me
to see her like this.

37:53.438 --> 37:56.640
I don't want to be left with
these last memories of her.

37:56.642 --> 37:58.708
Does she still remember you?

37:58.710 --> 37:59.609
I think so.

38:00.846 --> 38:02.512
Maybe, I can't
tell you for sure,

38:02.514 --> 38:04.381
but she does feel
comfortable when I'm around

38:04.383 --> 38:05.015
so that's good.

38:05.017 --> 38:06.900
Yeah.

38:06.901 --> 38:08.784
So how is it, she just
forgets a lot of things.

38:09.755 --> 38:11.238
No, that's what I thought

38:11.239 --> 38:12.722
that she would just
keep forgetting things,

38:12.724 --> 38:15.358
but it got worse and worse.

38:16.061 --> 38:19.562
It's a neurological disorder
so it kills your brain cells.

38:19.564 --> 38:21.665
So, yes, it's starting
with her forgetting things,

38:21.667 --> 38:23.566
- but everyone forgets things.
- Yeah.

38:23.568 --> 38:25.335
So we never really
put it down to more

38:25.337 --> 38:28.438
than just her doing too
many things and forgetting.

38:28.440 --> 38:30.640
But then it got worse and worse.

38:31.543 --> 38:36.446
Like she would drive and
forget where she was.

38:37.516 --> 38:38.748
Forget how to get home.

38:41.386 --> 38:44.654
This last time she
called me and was stuck

38:44.656 --> 38:48.591
in the middle of the road
in rush hour, freaking out.

38:48.593 --> 38:49.893
She didn't even know
how she got there.

38:49.895 --> 38:51.695
Oh shit.

38:51.697 --> 38:53.430
I was worried about
her for months.

38:53.432 --> 38:54.798
She was crying so much.

38:55.934 --> 38:57.767
I took her to see a
professor in Barcelona

38:57.769 --> 39:00.537
and they did a bunch
of tests and stuff.

39:00.539 --> 39:02.339
They diagnosed her
soon after that.

39:03.508 --> 39:06.476
So it's not like with
The Notebook then.

39:06.478 --> 39:08.712
Flashbacks of memories.

39:08.714 --> 39:10.847
It's no love story, trust me.

39:10.849 --> 39:12.582
It's sad.

39:12.584 --> 39:14.984
I'm literally watching
her age backwards.

39:14.986 --> 39:17.587
When you're born,
you know nothing.

39:18.457 --> 39:20.490
And they even have
to hold your head up.

39:20.492 --> 39:21.624
But you learn, adapt.

39:22.794 --> 39:24.594
Everything you
could do right now,

39:24.596 --> 39:26.696
at one point you
couldn't do that, right?

39:27.599 --> 39:30.567
You develop skills
to communicate and

39:30.569 --> 39:31.601
and find yourself.

39:31.603 --> 39:37.507
She's literally going
backwards, losing her identity.

39:37.509 --> 39:39.542
She's growing up
to be an infant.

39:39.544 --> 39:41.711
It's sad, it's so sad.

39:41.713 --> 39:43.580
She's in her own world.

39:43.582 --> 39:48.485
Mumbles all day with memories
in her scattered mind.

39:48.487 --> 39:49.853
No comprehension of the world.

39:52.457 --> 39:54.624
I'm really sorry, Annalisa.

39:54.626 --> 39:55.725
It's life, right?

39:55.727 --> 39:57.694
It's life and it's real.

39:58.864 --> 40:00.630
I just have to accept it.

40:00.632 --> 40:02.031
And I accept it.

40:03.001 --> 40:04.534
Like I was saying
before, she's going back

40:04.536 --> 40:06.603
from where she came
and that's life.

40:08.106 --> 40:11.040
I just don't want her
to lose her dignity.

40:11.042 --> 40:13.443
She always looked
after herself so much.

40:13.445 --> 40:14.544
Took pride in herself.

40:14.546 --> 40:17.647
Always so stylish,
dressed so well.

40:18.917 --> 40:21.718
The apple doesn't fall
far from the tree.

40:21.720 --> 40:23.019
You remember what
my Dad said about

40:23.021 --> 40:24.554
no one getting out alive?

40:28.493 --> 40:29.659
It's true.

40:29.661 --> 40:30.560
I mean...

40:31.830 --> 40:34.497
I think everyone
wastes a lot of time.

40:34.499 --> 40:36.166
Everyone takes time for granted.

40:37.469 --> 40:39.669
We can spend days,
weeks, months...

40:39.671 --> 40:41.104
People spend a lifetime
getting caught up

40:41.106 --> 40:42.872
in things that are
so meaningless.

40:44.543 --> 40:46.576
I mean, old grudges against
family and loved one.

40:46.578 --> 40:50.713
But that's the thing, those
bonds, those relationships,

40:52.551 --> 40:53.650
they're special.

40:54.820 --> 40:55.819
And they're finite.

40:58.457 --> 41:01.624
Just knowing that we're
only going to be able

41:01.626 --> 41:03.092
to really connect
with just a few people

41:03.094 --> 41:04.894
throughout the
course of our lives.

41:06.665 --> 41:10.500
You know, we really
just have to cherish

41:10.502 --> 41:12.535
and hold on, protect, that love.

41:14.139 --> 41:16.539
Against anything the
